{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/understanding-na%C3%AFve-bayes-algorithm-f9816f6f74c0", "time": 1683016165.567795, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/understanding-na%C3%AFve-bayes-algorithm-f9816f6f74c0/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Understanding Na\u00efve Bayes algorithm | by Vaibhav Jayaswal | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Understanding Na\u00efve Bayes algorithm", "description": "Na\u00efve Bayes is a classification algorithm that is a probabilistic classifier based on Bayes theorem. Before getting into the intricacies of Na\u00efve Bayes, we first understand the Bayes theorem. Bayes\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Na\u00efve Bayes is a classification algorithm that is a probabilistic classifier based on Bayes theorem. Before getting into the intricacies of Na\u00efve Bayes, we first understand the Bayes theorem.", "Bayes theorem says that if event B has occurred, then we can find the probability of event A given B.Mathematically, Bayes theorem is represented as", "Where P(B) != 0 (!= refers to not equal)P(A|B) \u2014 the probability of event A given B (called posterior)P(B|A) \u2014 the probability of event B given A (called likelihood)P(A) \u2014 the probability of event A (called prior)P(B) \u2014 the probability of event B (called evidence)", "For example, if we have a query point X (d-dimensional Boolean vector), we have to predict which class (Y) it belongs to out of two. How to calculate the probability of Y given X?", "Think of how many combinations can exist if we have the above formula. X being a d-dimensional Boolean vector, 2^d possible combinations for vector X, and 2 for output (2 class classification). The total combinations are 2^(d+1) for P(X1, X2,\u2026\u2026, Xd|Y), which is massive and not effective in real-world scenarios.", "Na\u00efve Bayes handles that problem by making an assumption.", "Assumption \u2014 Each feature in the input vector is conditionally independent of other features.", "It states that A is conditionally independent of B given C.", "The numerator, i.e., P(X1, X2,\u2026., Xd|Y)*P(Y), is equivalent to the joint probability model and can be expressed as P(X1, X2,\u2026., Xd, Y). Then we can unfold it using conditional probability.", "On applying the assumption of conditional independence, it can be written as", "Therefore, the probability formula using conditional independence is", "If we have two classes, we can get the probability of the class Y for class 1 P(Y=1|X) and class 0 P(Y=0|X) given a query point (X). The class assigned to the query point is decided based on the MAP decision rule (maximum a posterior), i.e., the class with a higher probability given X (P(Y|X)).", "Given the features such as outlook, temperature, and windy, predict whether the conditions are appropriate for playing tennis or not.", "Since Na\u00efve Bayes follows conditional independence, we will calculate P(Xi|Yj) for all i in X and j in Y.", "We will calculate the likelihood tables.", "Outlook P(Outlook|class)- where outlook can be overcast, rain and sunny and class can be yes and no.", "Temperature P(Temperature|class)- where temperature can be hot, mild, and cool and class can be yes and no.", "Windy P(Windy |class) - where Windy can be strong and weak and class can be yes and no.", "So if we have a query point, how to calculate which class it belongs to?", "Given a query point X\u2019 =[sunny, cool, strong]", "P(X\u2019) is a constant term which is equal to", "From the likelihood table, we get the values required in the formula", "Since the probability of class \u2018No\u2019 given X\u2019 is higher than class \u2018Yes\u2019 given X\u2019, the query point belongs to class \u2018No\u2019.", "There are different types of NB, such as Gaussian Na\u00efve Bayes, which works well with continuous data, Multinomial Na\u00efve Bayes for text classification by using the frequency of each word in a document. Another type is Bernoulli Na\u00efve Bayes, which only works if the features take two values (0 and 1) similar to that in the binary Bag of Words model.", "Na\u00efve Bayes is a classification algorithm that works on the Bayes theorem with a conditional independence assumption. It works well in real-world applications that require low latency because of the low time and space complexity.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "A machine learning enthusiast. I have pursued my masters from Indian Institute of Technology, Bombay."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Ff9816f6f74c0&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Funderstanding-na%C3%AFve-bayes-algorithm-f9816f6f74c0&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Funderstanding-na%C3%AFve-bayes-algorithm-f9816f6f74c0&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Funderstanding-na%C3%AFve-bayes-algorithm-f9816f6f74c0&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav----------